            <fr:title text="Distance Measure">Distance Measure</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:source-path>/Users/longie/forest/trees/FA-0009.tree</fr:source-path>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A distance measure, or metric, is a function that defines a measure of distance between elements of a set. In a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000G.xml" addr="FA-000G" title="Metric Space">metric space</fr:link>, a distance function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d]]></fr:tex> satisfies the following properties for all points <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z]]></fr:tex> in the space:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>Non-negativity: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,y) \geq  0]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Identity of indiscernibles: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,y) = 0]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = y]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Symmetry: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,y) = d(y,x)]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Triangle inequality: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,z) \leq  d(x,y) + d(y,z)]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1639</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0005</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0005.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Infinite Dimensions">Infinite Dimensions</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:source-path>/Users/longie/forest/trees/FA-0005.tree</fr:source-path>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A vector space is said to be infinite-dimensional if it cannot be spanned by a finite number of vectors. In other words, there is no finite basis for the space.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Examples include function spaces like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C([a,b])]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p]]></fr:tex> spaces, sequence spaces, and Hilbert spaces like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[l^2]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1641</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0012</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0012.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Inner product space">Inner product space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:source-path>/Users/longie/forest/trees/FA-0012.tree</fr:source-path>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An inner product space is a vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> over the field of real or complex numbers, equipped with an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0013.xml" addr="FA-0013" title="Inner product">inner product</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  \cdot ,\cdot \rangle  : V \times  V \rightarrow  \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The inner product satisfies the following axioms for all vectors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u, v, w \in  V]]></fr:tex> and all scalars <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a \in  \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:strong>Linearity in the first argument:</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  au + v, w\rangle   = a\langle  u, w\rangle   + \langle  v, w\rangle  ]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:strong>Conjugate symmetry:</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  u, v\rangle   = \overline {\langle  v, u\rangle  }]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:strong>Positive definiteness:</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  v, v\rangle   \geq  0]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  v, v\rangle   = 0]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v = 0]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>From the inner product, we can define:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>A norm: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||v|| = \sqrt {\langle  v,v\rangle  }]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>A metric: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(u,v) = ||u-v||]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>The concept of orthogonality: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> are orthogonal if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  u,v\rangle   = 0]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>Common examples of inner product spaces include <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex> with the dot product, the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C([a,b])]]></fr:tex> with the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2]]></fr:tex>-inner product <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  f,g \rangle  = \int _a^b f(x)\overline {g(x)}dx]]></fr:tex>, and the space of square-integrable functions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>A <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> is a complete inner product space.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1643</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0011</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0011.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Kronecker delta">Kronecker delta</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:source-path>/Users/longie/forest/trees/FA-0011.tree</fr:source-path>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The Kronecker delta, denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta _{ij}]]></fr:tex>, is a function of two variables, usually integers, that is 1 if the variables are equal and 0 otherwise. Formally:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta _{ij} =  \begin {cases}  1 & \text {if } i = j \\ 0 & \text {if } i \neq  j \end {cases}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>The Kronecker delta is widely used in many areas of mathematics, including linear algebra, tensor calculus, and functional analysis. In the context of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001H.xml" addr="FA-001H" title="Orthonormal set">orthonormal sets</fr:link> or bases in a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link>, the inner product of basis elements is given by the Kronecker delta:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  e_i, e_j \rangle  = \delta _{ij}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>This expresses the fact that the basis elements are orthogonal to each other (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  e_i, e_j \rangle  = 0]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i \neq  j]]></fr:tex>) and have unit norm (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  e_i, e_i \rangle  = 1]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1645</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0010</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0010.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Pointwise Convergence">Pointwise Convergence</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:source-path>/Users/longie/forest/trees/FA-0010.tree</fr:source-path>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A sequence of functions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{f_n\}]]></fr:tex> defined on a common domain <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> is said to converge pointwise to a function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> if for each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  D]]></fr:tex>, the sequence of numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{f_n(x)\}]]></fr:tex> converges to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Formally, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{f_n\}]]></fr:tex> converges pointwise to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> if for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  D]]></fr:tex> and every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε > 0]]></fr:tex>, there exists an integer <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N(x,ε)]]></fr:tex> such that:</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|f_n(x) - f(x)| < ε]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \geq  N(x,ε)]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>Note that the integer <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex> may depend on both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε]]></fr:tex>, which is a key distinction from <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001S.xml" addr="FA-001S" title="Uniform Convergence">uniform convergence</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Pointwise convergence is generally weaker than uniform convergence. A sequence of functions can converge pointwise without preserving many important properties of the functions, such as continuity, boundedness, or integrability.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
